2. Anti-Enclosure Covenant 


To preserve the public nature of this concept, the following additional clauses apply: 


2.1. No proprietary claims 


You may not assert or imply exclusive ownership over: 


the core idea of LLM-mediated cognitive spaces, 


the general conceptual architecture, 


the interaction principles, 


the idea of using LLMs to scaffold shared cognitive-linguistic environments.



2.2. No patents 


No element of this conceptual framework may be patented or placed under any exclusive IP claim.

Any attempt to do so grants an automatic royalty-free, irrevocable, worldwide license to the public. 


2.3. Derivatives must remain open 


Any derivative work must: 


remain openly accessible, 


remain free from proprietary enclosure, 


be compatible with CC BY-SA 4.0, 


and explicitly preserve the anti-enclosure clauses.



2.4. Transparency requirement 


If you create practical implementations (software, protocols, schemas, or interaction structures), you must document: 


the architecture, 


core methods, 


and governing principles,

in a publicly accessible form.



2.5. No platform lock-in 


Implementations may not: 


require exclusive use of a single proprietary platform, 


restrict export or reuse of cognitive structures, 


or create walled gardens around the idea.



2.6. Public benefit 


All implementations must acknowledge that the concept is intended as a public good, and applications must respect this purpose.



--- 


3. Summary (Not legally binding) 


You may use, share, modify, and build on this idea freely.

You may not privatize it.

Any work you create must remain open.

The idea belongs to everyone, permanently.


